<br>
Let me finish this with adding a few of my own comments.<br>
<br>
1) Haste.<br>
This is worth repeating since a lot of folks don't know it, bard haste does NOT stacking with any form of spell/proc/effect haste. Only the best haste applies.<br>
You can ONLY have 1 permanent haste + 1 song/spell/effect at a time.<br>
I repeat, does NOT stack with spell/proc/effect haste.<br>
Now, many of the bards haste songs have additional effects. These will in most cases stack and which is why you might see both a chanter haste and bard haste buff icons up at the same time. All components of both buffs will usually stack, EXCEPT the haste effect. Everyone got that now?<br>
Ok, so every rule has an exception...<br>
L50 and L60 and bard haste songs stack with EVERYTHING but not past the haste cap. BUT for a bard to use one of these song he must equip an instrument and the haste % is so pathetic that you wont see any bard using this if it's not a bard with his epic.<br>
<br>
2) The bard epic.<br>
This needs emphasizing. The bard epic works as all instrument types (as well as a weapon...), meaning that the bard don't have to juggle his instruments and weapons in order to play song that otherwise would REQUIRE an instrument.<br>
For example, invis song, the haste songs mentioned in 1) and occlusion of sound.<br>
Not only that, it also boosts ALL songs as if an instrument of the appropriate type was equipped.<br>
Not to mention the kick-ass proc on that weapon....<br>
Needless to say, this epic never leaves a bards hands once he gets it (except when he dies, but then it's still in his hands technically).<br>
<br>
3) Crowd control.<br>
Bards are excellent at CC, but there are a few things to remember before trusting this to the bard.<br>
Bards have a number of ways of doing CC, but the most common and least fatal (if used correctly) are, mez and charm.<br>
Bards get three forms of mez. First mez is gained at 15 and is actually an AE mez. Don't use this. Ever. It's hopelessly broken, but &quot;working as intended&quot; according to Verant. Second form of mez is gained at 28 and that worked quite good when I got it many years ago. Since then a secondary resist was added and now this will only land once in a blue moon. But the bard is stuck with that until 53. Then bards really shine at mezzing. The L53 song is so good that it has never left my song bank since I got it. A few things you need to know as the non-bard here, is that:<br>
1. Nothing above 55 can be mezzed with this. So if you're going to face multiple 56-60 mobs you better think of something else.<br>
2. This song needs to be refreshed every 3 ticks or so, so the most a bard can mez is 3 (or 4 if he's really good and on a fast machine with a solid connection) if he don't get too many resists.<br>
3. Make sure you know the bard, and that he know's how to mez. This applies to any class in any pick-up group situation. It's not the class/race that gets you killed, it's the moron behind the keyboard.<br>
4. If all 3 of the above is followed don't be surprised by what you can do. If you can't get an enchanter to accompany you, don't be afraid to ask the neighbourhood bard. In a lot of normal grouping situations the bard will do just as well as the chanter.<br>
<br>
A few words about charm. This will usually be the bards best form of CC before L53. There are two charm songs. The first one is a L27 song. It costs no mana and works on all mobs L1-37. L38+ mobs will have to be charmed with the second charm song, which is gained at L39 and works on all mobs L1-51. Nothing L52+ can be charmed by a bard. One thing to remember here is that the second song cost mana to use. Each pulse cost 20 mana. Let's say each charm lasts 15 seconds (high), thats 80 mana per minute to keep something charmed. For a L60 bard with 100 Int, that's 15 minutes worth of charm before he's OOM. Which brings me to..<br>
<br>
4) Manaregen.<br>
Nothing speed up a bards manaregen besides sitting. All those manasongs and none work on ourselves! This includes clarity etc. Not even +Mana items effects a bards manapool.<br>
 This means that after the bard dies there will be no CC in the form of charm for quite awhile (well, nothing L38+ that is).<br>
<br>
5) Manasong.<br>
Nothing makes the bard aggro on you as much as hearing that dreaded, &quot;manasong plz&quot;.<br>
If it's downtime, first make sure you haven't turned off all particle effects and bard-spamming before saying those words.<br>
Secondly, casters have a tendancy to scatter all over the room. If you are not getting the effects of manasong you are most likely out of range. In my oppinion it is NOT the bards duty to dance all over the room trying to get casters in range of the manasong. If you want manasong, go park your ass next to the bard, he's most likely already playing it while you're busy typing out your &quot;manasong plz&quot;.<br>
<br>
Read the above about the different forms of mana that the bard can provide. But I'm going to throw out some numbers there for you to think about.<br>
L32 song gives everyone in the group a shot of 7 mana on each pulse. L55 puts up a buff icon that last 3 ticks and gives the party 12 mana, 11 hp and stamina per tick.<br>
Over a minute that's 70 mana with L32 and 120 mana with L55. In a long fight, sure I'll start up manasong but consider those numbers before you ask the bard to turn on manasong during combat. There's alot of other things the bard can do to take out the mobs besides pumping mana to the casters.<br>
Just using myself as an exampel, if I were to equip my drum and start up all my DoT's that's almost 200hp/tick damage on one mob. Or how about 30% haste, +30 str, +30 agi, +21 AC on all party members PLUS 32% slow, -16 AC , -47 agi on one mob PLUS +32 MR/HR/CR, +6 AC on all party members.<br>
I could go on, but you get the idea.<br>
<br>
Think about it an extra time before starting to type out &quot;manasong plz&quot;<br>
<br>
Can't think of anything else but if I do I'll update this guide.<br>
